04704nam a22005415i 9780228004417DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280044177 a10.1515/97802280044172doi  a(DE-B1597)656862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ766.5.C3bD93 2020 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a363.9/60971090472231 aDyck, Erika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChallenging Choices :bCanada's Population Control in the 1970s /cErika Dyck, Maureen Lux. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v5500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tMaking a New Mainstream -- tPolitics of Health in the Global North -- tIndigenous Women in the Provincial South -- tSex and Responsibility in the Community -- tVasectomies and the Dilemma of Male Reproduction -- tTeenagers and the Economics of Abortion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween the decriminalization of contraception in 1969 and the introduction of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms in 1982, a landmark decade in the struggle for women's rights, public discourse about birth control and family planning was transformed. At the same time, a transnational conversation about the "population bomb" that threatened global famine caused by overpopulation embraced birth control technologies for a different set of reasons, revisiting controversial ideas about eugenics, heredity, and degeneration. In Challenging Choices Erika Dyck and Maureen Lux argue that reproductive politics in 1970s Canada were shaped by competing ideologies on global population control, poverty, personal autonomy, race, and gender. For some Canadians the 1970s did not bring about an era of reproductive liberty but instead reinforced traditional power dynamics and paternalistic structures of authority. Dyck and Lux present case studies of four groups of Canadians who were routinely excluded from progressive, reformist discourse: Indigenous women and their communities, those with intellectual and physical disabilities, teenage girls, and men. In different ways, each faced new levels of government regulation, scrutiny, or state intervention as they negotiated their reproductive health, rights, and responsibilities in the so-called era of sexual liberation. While acknowledging the reproductive rights gains that were made in the 1970s, the authors argue that the legal changes affected Canadians differently depending on age, social position, gender, health status, and cultural background. Illustrating the many ways to plan a modern family, these case studies reveal how the relative merits of life and choice were pitted against each other to create a new moral landscape for evaluating classic questions about population control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBirth controlxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCasestudies. 0aBirth controlxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCasestudies. 0aReproductive healthxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aReproductive healthxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aReproductive rightsxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aReproductive rightsxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aLux, Maureen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://